<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="ea5ed00c-452a-5eb6-a87d-5d658ac916c5" activityNameId="625ced3c-ca13-44f5-89ae-10b52e792673" parentActivityId="e6d2646f-41a5-5f4b-a1b4-2e1401ad0b3b" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">zinc oxide production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Chinese White</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Snow white</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Amalox</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Oxozinc</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">zinc white</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Permanent White</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">ZINC OXIDE</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From reception of raw materials at the factory gate.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of zinc oxide. This dataset includes the input of zinc scrap (for which iron scrap is used as proxy). The consumption of air is not included. The dataset also includes the estimated energy demand and infrastructure of the plant. Solid wastes and water consumption are omitted.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of solid zinc oxide powder. Zinc oxide, formerly also called zinc white, is a fine white powder that turns yellow when heated above 300 °C. Zinc oxide is mainly produced from residues and secondary zinc. It is used mainly in the rubber industry as a vulcanization activator or sometimes as a filler. Tires contain up to 5% zinc. Another application for zinc oxide is the use as an additive in fertilizers or in animal feed, as a dietary supplement to overcome potential zinc deficiencies. Zinc oxide is also used in the cosmetic industry for lipsticks, powders and sunscreens. Other applications of zinc oxide, such as fillers in lubricants, are of minor importance.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Three different processes are used to produce zinc oxide: about 1 – 2 % of zinc oxide is produced by the wet process, 10 – 20 % by the direct process, and the remainder by the indirect (or French) process. This dataset represents the production of zinc oxide out of secondary zinc materials by means of the indirect (or French) way. The inventory is estimated based on literature and expert judgement and represents therefore a rough estimation of the process requirements and should therefore be used only for processes where the impact of zinc oxide is not considered to be high.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier R., Classen M., Lehmann M. and Scharnhorst W. (2007) Life cycle inventories of Electric and Electronic Equipment: Production, Use and Disposal. ecoinvent report No. 18. Empa / Technology &amp; Society Lab, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, 2007.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Auer, G., Woditsch, P., Westerhaus, A., Kischkewitz, J., Griebler, W.-D. and De Liedekerke, M. 2009. Pigments, Inorganic, 2. White Pigments. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Schwab, B., Ruh, A., Manthey, J. and Drosik, M. 2015. Zinc. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–25.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data used has no specific geographical origin (stoichiometry). The electricity consumption is based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. It is assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Zinc oxide is mainly produced from residues and secondary zinc by means of the indirect (or French) way. The demand for chemical purity imposed by the users means that a number of purification techniques are required. About 1 – 2 % of zinc oxide is produced by the wet process, 10 – 20 % by the direct process, and the remainder by the indirect process.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Hischier R., Classen M., Lehmann M. and Scharnhorst W. (2007) Life cycle inventories of Electric and Electronic Equipment: Production, Use and Disposal. ecoinvent report No. 18. Empa / Technology &amp; Society Lab, Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, 2007.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Auer, G., Woditsch, P., Westerhaus, A., Kischkewitz, J., Griebler, W.-D. and De Liedekerke, M. 2009. Pigments, Inorganic, 2. White Pigments. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Schwab, B., Ruh, A., Manthey, J. and Drosik, M. 2015. Zinc. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. 1–25.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2005-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Date of published literature. The electricity consumption is based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="b1917b3b-2084-5713-85bb-55fda3e7be15" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" casNumber="001314-13-2" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="77ad34b3-7b53-412e-afbb-0536fb8d5c6a" productionVolumeAmount="76460176.9911504" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV" productionVolumeMathematicalRelation="10E8*0.3*(1.44E+13/5.65E+13)">
        <name xml:lang="en">zinc oxide</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Zinc oxide formerly also called zinc white, is a fine white powder that turns yellow when heated above 300 °C.
Historically seen, Zinc oxide was a byproduct of copper smelting. Already the Romans knew this substance that they called 'cadmia'. In the 18th century, the process to produce ZnO by the combustion of metallic zinc has been discovered, and in 1840 industrial production was started by Leclaire (indirect or French process). The use of this white pigment spread rapidly. Zinc oxide replaced white lead because it had the advantage of being nontoxic, of not darkening in the presence of sulfurous gases, and of having better hiding power. In parallel the process in a roasting furnace was developed in which a grate is charged with coal and then covered with a mixture of zinc ore and coal. Here zinc is reduced by the partial combustion of the coal and reoxidized at the furnace exit (direct or American process). However, this second process is today no longer used. A third industrial production process exists but this wet process is less widely used.</comment>
        <property propertyId="f2283db2-62e4-467f-b9ac-c4f45be563b4" amount="0.0" isDefiningValue="false" isCalculatedAmount="false" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
